\section{Introduction}
The theoretical basis for modelling human-environment feedbacks has advanced considerably in recent years with the emergence of socio-hydrology; a discipline within the hydrological sciences which formally recognizes the interdependencies between social and hydrological systems and seeks to understand the complex relationships which govern their co-evolution in time and space \citep{montanari_panta_2013,savenije_evolving_2014,sivapalan_time_2015,kuil_exploring_2018}. Mirroring trends in hydrological research more broadly, modelling has emerged as an important mode of inquiry in socio-hydrological research \citep{}. In contrast to the problem-focussed approach adopted water resource management, socio-hydrological models have tended to focus on understanding the mechanisms which govern the system behaviour (commonly referred to in the literature as a positivist approach) \citep{pande_progress_2017}. Accordingly, existing quantitative socio-hydrological models mainly consist of coupled, non-linear differential equations which focus on the temporal dynamics of coupled human-water systems \citep{pande_progress_2017}. Several models consist of stylized relationships which are intended to develop hypotheses about the system and explore its behaviour under different scenarios of social and environmental change \citep[e.g.][]{van_emmerik_socio-hydrologic_2014,di_baldassarre_debates-perspectives_2015,garcia_question_2016}. \\

Low dimensional models have proven adept at highlighting the aggregated response of a system to change \citep{}, identifying data gaps... \citep{di_baldassarre_debates-perspectives_2015}. However, in many contexts such models are ill-suited to exploring the co-evolution of human systems and watershed hydrology, and may fail to capture important dynamics such as... Modelling the aggregate response of the social domain to changes in the physical domain often poorly translate to insights which are relevant to individuals, whose behaviour... \citep{}. For example, canal systems... System dynamics is inherently top-down... approaches are typically poor at... bottom-up change \citep{}... unless the mechanism is known and explicitly parameterised \citep{}. Lastly, the use of empirical relationships to control the evolution of state variables means that they do not easily scale or translate to other regions \citep{}. From the perspective of developing theory... this is not a cause for concern. However, ... For this reason the scale and type of problems that can be addressed are somewhat limited. Water resources management. Current socio-hydrological models are spatially lumped or semi-distributed. % To advance further, there is a need to develop more realistic models which are capable of providing insight into socio-hydrological systems rather than simply reinforcing what is already known \citep{troy_debates-perspectives_2015,loucks_debates-perspectives_2015,blair_socio-hydrological_2016}. This will involve more complete models of human behaviour \citep{loucks_debates-perspectives_2015}, as well as more accurate models of hydrological systems \citep{gober_debates-perspectives_2015,mount_data-driven_2016}. In order to simulate the magnitude and direction of change in system state variables it is necessary to accurately capture the underlying hydrological processes, such as river discharge, groundwater dynamics and root zone hydrology \citep{}. Models capable... Hence, there is a clear... to improve the representation of human processes in distributed hydrological models. \\

