Developing spatially-explicit models... There is a disconnect between the scale (both in time and space) at which hydrological and human processes occur. In regions dominated by smallholder farms, such as northern India, ... Agent-based modelling has been identified as a promising approach for socio-hydrological research \citep[e.g][]{blair_???_2015}. Such models consist of a set of individuals (``agents'') who each behave and interact with each other according to a set of rules, which may be constant during the simulation, or evolve (?). However, these models are computationally intensive and have large data requirements, which effectively precludes their use beyond a certain number of agents \citep{}. Ecologists developed the concept of a ``super-individual'' to efficiently model the behaviour of very large populations. A super-individual is a model object which is broadly considered as an individual but which in fact represents a group of \textit{n} individuals \citep{scheffer_super-individuals_1995}. The selection of individuals from the population to be combined in a super-individual is based on defined characteristics of each individual \citep{scheffer_super-individuals_1995}. \\

To explore the use of super-individuals in socio-hydrological research, we have... developed a farmer decision model for simulating farmer behaviour with respect to decisions about irrigation and farm investment \citep{okeeffe_???_2018}, and integrated this with a gridded regional hydrological model. The framework has been developed using a ``bottom-up'' approach, using field-level observations to define a range of plausible actions that a farmer may take in response to various biophysical and socioeconomic state variables. The regional hydrological model consists of ... modules representing surface water hydrology and crop production, river and canal routing and two-dimensional groundwater dynamics, allowing us to explore the co-evolution of the human and hydrological system in space and time. In this paper, we describe the model development... including ... in a spatially distributed framework. We use the coupled model to explore the socio-hydrology of the Indo-Gangetic Plain, a region which is representative of many of the water management challenges we face today, particularly with respect to human-environment competition for water resources. We elucidate a number... conjunctive water use. \\

