In developing the model, we follow the question-driven process set out by \citet{garcia_question_2016}. This approach recognises that coupled human-environment systems can never be modelled exhaustively \citep{}, but should instead focus on the variables and processes which are necessary to answer clearly defined research questions. Bearing in mind the epistomological uncertainties associated... the approach advocates the backward-reasoning approach set out in \citet{schluter_application_2014}, whereby the research question... This approach is most suited to modelling where the epistomological uncertainty about the system is insufficient... \citep{arocha_???_1993}; furthermore, it enables the modeller to focus... Considering the perceptual model, we identified the interplay between the canal system, the underlying aquifer and the agricultural system as a key area of interest. Accordingly, we define the key question we wish to ask of the model as, \textit{What is the influence of the canal system on the livelihood of smallholder farmers in the Indo-Gangetic Plain, and how does this vary in time and space?}. \\

There are two key outcome metrics that will help us to answer the research question. The first metric is smallholder livelihood, which we equate to the accumulated capital of smallholders \citep{pande_socio-hydrological_2016,okeeffe_including_2018}. From our perceptual model we can identify a number of key processes which influence the outcome metric and must therefore be included in the conceptual model. The dynamics of the groundwater system influences the cost of abstracting irrigation water as well as the baseflow contribution to streamflow. Recharge to the aquifer is governed by the surface hydrological processes as well as canal leakage. Subsequently, we identify the key variables and relationships to include in our model. These are depicted graphically in Figure X. The resulting model may be considered in terms of four coupled subsystems representing the river system, the canal system, the groundwater system, and the agricultural system. The governing equations of these subsystems are set out below.

While models which include human-environment feedbacks and interactions are diverse, there are some commonalities between applications which should be considered to a greater or lesser extent. According to \citet{elshafei_prototype_2014}, the important facets of a coupled human-water system to consider during conceptualisation are: catchment hydrology, population dynamics, economics, ecosystem services, societal sensitivity and behavioural response. Adapting this approach for the Indo-Gangetic Plain, we conceptualize the system in terms of four subsystems, representing the river system, the canal system, the groundwater system and the agricultural system. \\

Considering the above points... Figure~X shows the spatial extent and key physical features of the study area. We have chosen to extend the model region beyond the surface catchment boundary in order to include the two canal command areas as well as to utilise physically realistic boundaries for the hydrogeological system. These boundaries consist of the Ganges river to the south, the X and Y rivers to the east and west, respectively, and the Himalaya to the north. We run the model between 1980 and 2010, covering most of the operational period of the Gandak barrage and canal system. \\

The research question... From the socio-economic point of view, the phenomena we are interested in include the growth in irrigated area and the extent to which this has been driven by the number of tubewells in operation. Moreover, we are interested in the associated feedbacks with farmer livelihood in the basin. From a hydrological perspective, we are interested in the extent to which the operation of canals and tubewells for the purpose of irrigation has influenced river flows in the basin, and the potential impact this has had on the habitats of endangered species.\\

Of the various facets of socio-hydrological model outlined by \citet{elshafei_???_2014}, we choose to externalize certain variables and processes. Soil fertility is a considerable problem across much of the Indo-Gangetic Plain ... Intensive agricultural practices [and crop selection] have led to declining soil fertility across the region \citep{}, forcing farmers to increase their use of chemical fertiliser (Figure X). The problem is most acute amongst smallholder farmers who cannot afford the short-term loss in productivity associated with the introduction of a fallow period \citep{}. Consequently the area of fallow land across the Indo-Gangetic Plain is in decline \citep{}, and farmers report that fertiliser costs make up a substantial portion of their annual expenditure. Further, we do not consider here the feedbacks between water availability and management in the basin and the various institutions charged with implementing policies... This is largely due to a lack of data on these processes, and uncertainty... Instead, we develop various scenarios of water management... to explore the impact of water management scenarios on... \\

