\subsection{Surface hydrology}
The surface hydrology module is based on a ``leaky bucket'' model adopted in several regional hydrological models, including PCR-GLOBWB \citep{van_beek_global_2011} and the Community Water Model. The purpose of the module is to solve the surface water balance, which may be expressed as

% TODO: symbols!!!
\begin{equation}
  \frac{dS}{dt}(t) = P(t) + Irr(t) + CR(t) - ET_{c}(t) - RO(t) - R(t) - I(t),
\end{equation}

\noindent where $\frac{dS}{dt}(t)$ is the change in storage in the root zone of an elemental area at time $t$, $P(t)$ is precipitation, $Irr(t)$ is irrigation, $ET_{c}(t)$ is actual evapotranspiration, $RO(t)$ is surface runoff, $R(t)$ is recharge from the base of the soil layer and $I$ is canopy interception ($ML^{-2}T^{-1}$).\\

% See "Large-scale groundwater modeling using global datasets: a test case for the Rhine-Meuse basin" by Sutanudjaja et al 2011 for detail about the PCR-GLOBWB interception scheme

% ~~~~~~~~~~~~
% Interception
% ~~~~~~~~~~~~
The vegetation canopy is modelled as a single reservoir with capacity $s_{c}(t)$ ($\mathrm{M L^{-2}}$). Precipitation fills the reservoir to its maximum capacity, $s_{c,max}$, with excess water falling as throughfall,

\begin{equation} \label{eq:throughfall}
  P_{t}(t) =
  \begin{cases}
    P(t) - (S_{c,max} - S_{c}), & \text{if}\ P(t) + s_{c}(t-1) > s_{c,max}\\
    0, & \text{otherwise}.
\end{cases}
\end{equation}

% ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
% Surface runoff
% ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
We model surface runoff using the Improved Arno scheme \citep{todini_arno_1996,hagemann_improving_2003}, in which the soil water storage of a catchment is represented as a distribution, such that for a given average soil water content $W(t)$ a proportion of the area will be at saturation and thus capable of producing runoff \citep{} (see Appendix A for a full derivation of the Improved Arno scheme). According to this procedure, which is further expanded by \citet{vanbeek_???_2009}, the saturated fraction of an area is calculated according to the average water storage as follows

\begin{equation}
  x = 1 - \left(\frac{W_{max} - W(t)}{W_{max} - W_{min}}\right)^{\frac{b}{b+1}}
\end{equation}

where $W_{max}$ and $W_{min}$ are the maximum and minimum average storage, respectively, and $b$ is a dimensionless shape parameter which defines the distribution of soil water storage. Surface runoff $q_{r}(t)$ ($\mathrm{L T^{-1}}$) is related to the average soil water content $W(t)$ according to the following scheme:

\begin{enumerate}
\item $P_{t}(t) < W_{min} - W(t)$,
  \begin{equation}
    q_{r}(t) = 0
  \end{equation}

\item $W_{min} - W(t) \leq P_{t}(t) < \left(b+1\right) \left(W_{max} - W_{min}\right) \left[\frac{W_{max} - W(t)}{W_{max} - W_{min}}\right]^{\frac{1}{b+1}}$,
  \begin{multline}
    q_{r}(t) = P_{t}(t) - (W_{max} - W(t)) \\
    + (W_{max} - W_{min}) \left[ \left(\frac{W_{max} - W(t)}{W_{max} - W_{min}} \right)^{\frac{1}{b+1}} - \frac{P_{t}(t)}{\left(b+1\right) \left(W_{max} - W_{min}\right)} \right]^{b+1}
  \end{multline}
  
\item $P_{t}(t) \geq \left(b+1\right) \left(W_{max} - W_{min}\right) \left[\frac{W_{max} - W(t)}{W_{max} - W_{min}}\right]^{\frac{1}{b+1}}$,
  \begin{equation}
    q_{r}(t) = P_{t}(t) - (W_{max} - W(t))
  \end{equation}
\end{enumerate}

The effective precipitation is then computed as the difference between throughfall and surface runoff:

\begin{equation}
  P_{e}(t) = P_{t}(t) - q_{r}(t)
\end{equation}

% ~~~~~~~~~~~~
% Infiltration
% ~~~~~~~~~~~~
\noindent In the saturated portion of the area we allow a proportion of net precipitation to bypass the root zone as preferential flow:

\begin{equation}
  q_{p}(t) = x \phi P_{e}(t)
\end{equation}

\noindent where $\phi$ is a dimensionless coefficient. Infiltration to the soil coloumn is then the difference between the effective precipitation and preferential flow,

\begin{equation}
  I(t) = P_{e}(t) - q_{p}(t).
\end{equation}

\noindent We represent the root zone as three layers: an upper layer with a fixed depth of $0.05m$, and two additional layers which vary in size according to the land cover type. A fourth layer represents the groundwater store. The downward fluxes from the upper three soil layers are set equal to the unsaturated hydraulic conductivity, $k(\theta_{E})$ ($\mathrm{L T^{-1}}$), such that

\begin{align*}
  q_{1 \rightarrow 2}(t) &= k_{1}(\theta_{E,1})\\
  q_{2 \rightarrow 3}(t) &= k_{2}(\theta_{E,2})\\
  q_{3 \rightarrow 4}(t) &= k_{3}(\theta_{E,3})
\end{align*}

\noindent where $\theta_{E}$ is the degree of saturation of a given soil layer, computed as

\begin{equation}
  \theta_{E} = \frac{W_{max} + b \left(W_{max} - W_{min}\right) \left[1 - \frac{b+1}{b} \left(\frac{W_{max} - W}{W_{max} - W_{min}}\right)^{\frac{1}{b+1}}\right]}{W_{max} + b \left(W_{max} - W_{min}\right) \left[1 - \left(\frac{W_{max} - W}{W_{max} - W_{min}}\right)^{\frac{1}{b+1}}\right]}
\end{equation}

\noindent where $\theta(t)$ is the actual water content of the soil layer, and $\theta_{r}$ and $\theta_{s}$ are respectively the residual and saturated volumetric water contents ($\mathrm{M L^{-3}}$).\\

Recharge is then computed as the sum of the downward flux from the bottom soil layer and preferential flow:

\begin{equation}
  R(t) = q_{3 \rightarrow 4}(t) + q_{p}(t).
\end{equation}

% ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
% Evapotranspiration
% ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

Following \citet{allen_???_1998}, we estimate potential crop evapotranspiration as

\begin{equation}
  ET_{c}(t) = k_{c}(t)ET_{0}(t)
\end{equation}

\noindent where $ET_{0}(t) $ is reference potential evapotranspiration ($\mathrm{M L^{-2}}$), and $k_{c}(t)$ is the crop coefficient (dimensionless). We first compute the evaporative flux from the canopy store ($\mathrm{M L^{-2}}$), as follows

\begin{equation}
  E_{c}(t) =
  \begin{cases}
    ET_{o}(t)k_{c}(t), & \text{if}\ ET_{o}(t)k_{c}(t) \leq s_{c}(t)\\
    s_{c}(t), & \text{otherwise}.
  \end{cases}
\end{equation}

\noindent We separate the remaining energy ($ET_{c}(t) - E_{c}(t)$) into its constituent parts in order to model separately the various limiting processes. Hence the potential soil evaporation and transpiration are calculated as

\begin{equation}
  E_{p,s}(t) = k_{c,min} \left(ET_{0}(t) - E_{c}(t)\right)
\end{equation}

\noindent and

\begin{equation}
  E_{p,T}(t) = \left(k_{c} - k_{c,min}\right) \left(ET_{0}(t) - E_{c}(t)\right),
\end{equation}

\noindent respectively, where $k_{c,min}$ is the minimum crop factor for bare soil which we assume to equal $0.20$ \citep{vanbeek_global_2011}. We assume that soil evaporation is extracted from the surface soil layer only and is limited by the hydraulic conductivity of that layer, such that the actual soil evaporation may be expressed as

\begin{equation}
  E_{a,s}(t) = x min\left(k_{s}, E_{s}\right) + \left(1 - x\right) \left[k(\theta_{E1}), E_{s}\right]
\end{equation}

\noindent where $k_{s}(t)$ and is the saturated hydraulic conductivity, $k(\theta_{E1})$ is the unsaturated hydraulic conductivity, and $\theta_{E1}$ is the effective degreee of saturation of the surface soil layer. We assume that transpiration cannot take place in saturated areas due to a lack of aeration \citep{}. In unsaturated areas potential transpiration is limited by a water stress coefficient $k_{s}(t)$ (dimensionless) \citep{allen_???_1998}, such that

\begin{equation} \label{eq:tact}
  E_{a,T} = \left(1 - x\right) k_{s}(t) E_{p,T}(t)
\end{equation}

\noindent and

\begin{equation}
  k_{s}(t) = \frac{TAW(t) - D_{r}(t)}{(1 - p) TAW(t)},
\end{equation}

\noindent where

\begin{equation}
  TAW(t) = \frac{\theta_{fc} - \theta_{wp}} Z_{r}(t),
\end{equation}

\noindent $D_{r}$ is the root zone depletion ($\mathrm{L}$), $p$ is the depletion factor (dimensionless), and $Z_{r}$ is the rooting depth ($\mathrm{L}$). In Equation~\ref{eq:tact} we use the average value of $k_{s}(t)$, which is computed for each soil compartment and weighed according to the total soil water storage and root fraction.\\

\subsection{Irrigation demand}
% The use of flood irrigation at set intervals contrasts with the soil moisture based approaches (whereby irrigation is applied whenever the soil moisture falls below some threshold, which is usually based on field capacity) commonly employed in regional water use models \citep[e.g.][]{}.
The crop water demand is the amount of water required by a crop to ensure it is unaffected by water stress during the growing season. If precipitation is insufficient to meet this demand then crop evapotranspiration will fall below potential rate \citep{}. Hence, following \citep{wada_nonsustainable_2012}, we assume the irrigation demand to equal the difference between actual and potential evapotranspiration, as follows

\begin{equation}
  I_{d}(t) = (E_{p,T}(t) - E_{a,T}(t)) + (E_{p,s} - E_{a,s}),
\end{equation}

\noindent where the $E_{a,T}(t)$ and $E_{p,T}(t)$ are the actual evapotranspiration terms that would occur if the crop did not receive irrigation.\\

\subsection{Irrigation supply}
The reliability of the canal network is an important influence on farm-level water management decisions \citep{okeeffe_including_2018}. In general, the reliability of the canal network is related to the distance from the canal head, with farmers near the head receiving a more reliable service, and farmers near the tail receiving a less reliable service \citep{}. We assume that farmers initially attempt to meet the irrigation demand from the canal, such that the irrigation supply from the canal system is computed as

\begin{equation}
  I_{s,c}(t) =
  \begin{cases}
    I_{d}(t), & \text{if}\ I_{d}(t) \leq q_{c}(t)\\
    q_{c}(t), & \text{otherwise}.
  \end{cases}  
\end{equation}

\noindent where $q_{c}$ is the canal supply ($\mathrm{L T^{-1}}$). The irrigation water demand is subsequently removed from the canal (TODO, after Chris writes canal model section).\\

If farmers do not have access to the canal network, or if the canal does not contain sufficient water to meet the irrigation demand, we assume that farmers seek to exploit the groundwater resource. The maximum quantity of water which can be abstracted from a single tubewell is governed by the empirical equation of \cite{}, expressed

\begin{equation}
  Q_{w}(t) = \frac{t_{w} \times 129574.1 \times BHP}{d + ((255.5998 \times BHP^2) / (d^2 \times D^4))}
\end{equation}

% TODO: sort out units
\noindent where $Q_{w}(t)$ is well discharge in litres ($\mathrm{M T^{-1}}$), $t_{w}$ is the duration of the irrigation event in hours ($\mathrm{T}$), $BHP$ is the horsepower of the pump ($\mathrm{}$), $d$ is the average depth of the well in metres ($\mathrm{L}$), and $D$ is the diameter of the suction pipe in inches ($\mathrm{L}$). Hence the total supply of groundwater may be expressed as

\begin{equation}
  I_{g}(t) = I_{total}(t) - I_{c}(t)
  \begin{cases}
    I_{total}(t) - I_{c}(t), & \text{if}\ I_{total}(t) - I_{c}(t) \leq Q_{w}(t)\\
    Q_{w}(t), & \text{otherwise}.
  \end{cases}    
\end{equation}

\noindent and the total irrigation supply is

\begin{equation}
  I_{s}(t) = I_{c}(t) + I_{w}(t).
\end{equation}

\noindent The irrigation supply is added to throughfall, so that Equation~\ref{throughfall} becomes

\begin{equation} \label{eq:throughfall}
  P_{t}(t) =
  \begin{cases}
    P(t) - (S_{c,max} - S_{c}) + I_{s}(t), & \text{if}\ P(t) + s_{c}(t-1) > s_{c,max}\\
    I_{s}(t), & \text{otherwise}.
\end{cases}
\end{equation}

\noindent The daily irrigation demand deficit is computed by subtracting the irrigation supply from the irrigation demand. This is accumulated during the growing season and used in the farm economics module to inform decisions about potential investments.\\

