We transferred the conceptual model to a distributed modelling framework with a spatial resolution of 5 arcminutes $\times$ 5 arcminutes. Subgrid heterogeneity is represented using the tiling approach adopted in many distributed hydrological and Earth system models \citep[e.g.][]{}. Accordingly, we represent the land surface in terms of three vegetated land covers (forest, grassland, and cropland) and two non-vegetated land covers (impervious land, water). The cropland land cover type is further divided along two dimensions. The first dimension divides cropland into a set of farms for which the livelihood model outlined above can be implemented separately, accounting for heterogeneity in the socioeconomic domain. The second dimension divides cropland into a set of specific crop types, accounting for the fact that individual crops have particular physical and socioeconomic characteristics. Figure~\ref{} illustrates the subgrid scheme. \\

A number of methodological issues arise. ``...both the natural system and human dimension are reduced to fit in a quantitative model''. As \citet{wesselink_socio-hydrology_2017} point out, ``humans differ from other constituents of socio-hydrological models because they can choose how to act on their perception and preferences...''. One approach to dealing with this heterogeneity is to split populations into categories according to particular attributes which are relevant for the field of study. For example, \citet{srinivasan_hydrologic_2010}... Representing heterogeneity in populations in sufficient detail is a problem commonly encountered in computational ecology... Where possible, agent-based models are often used \citep[e.g.][]{}. However, in some situations this becomes computationally infeasible. The super-individual approach... \citep{}. \\

