\subsubsection{Crop characteristics}
Although a wide variety of crops are grown in the study region, the vast majority of farms implement a rice-wheat or rice-rice crop rotation. In some parts of the basin, especially in the upper reaches, sugarcane is an important cash crop. While \textit{kharif} crops may be grown under rainfed or irrigated conditions, \textit{rabi} crops are almost always irrigated. Sugarcane, an annual crop, also tends to be grown under irrigated conditions in order to ensure an adequate supply of water during the \textit{rabi} season. The required crop parameters are shown in Table X. We used potential yield from the FAO Global Agro-Ecological Zones database. Crop calendars, which detail the approximate planting date and growing season length of the various crops, were compiled from the MIRCA2000 dataset \citep{portmann_???_2010} and national data \citep{moulds_???_20XX}. We used the relative length of crop growth stages (initial, development) and maximum rooting depth from the Global Crop Water Model \citep{siebert}. Lastly, we used crop coefficients for the X growth stages rice and wheat from \citet{}, and from GCWM for sugarcane.

