\section{Discussion}
% Paragraph 1: summary of model, its aims and objectives
In this paper we have developed a spatially distributed model to capture the co-evolutionary dynamics of a coupled human-water system. The model we have described attempts to advance socio-hydrological modelling by adapting a farm-scale model to a spatially-explicit modelling framework in which the hydrological boundary conditions are provided by a coupled model framework. A key feature of the modelling framework is its reliance on primary data collection. The model was developed from field data presented in \citet{okeeffe_???_2016} and \citet{okeeffe_???_2018}. Mention number of data points in comparison to the number of farmers. Together with space and time dimensions, we add a cross-cutting human dimension within which we can explore the effects of diverse human behaviour on water resources, and vice versa. We have focused on human activities related to agricultural water management. Highlight importance of primary data collection which is specific to the catchment under consideration. Emphasise the role of models as a conceptual representation of a system, and the need for continual dialogue between field work and model development. The development of the model has been informed by a number of farmer interviews and focus groups \citep{okeeffe}, as well as knowledge of the study region built up over several years \citep{atree}. \\

% Paragraph 2+: discussion of results (TODO)
We applied the model to the Gandak basin in northern India, which is representative of many of the water management challenges which occur across the Indo-Gangetic Plain, and performed a scenario analysis to explore the impact of the canal system on the system dynamics across space and time. \\

% Paragraph 3: discussion of model development
The emergence of socio-hydrology and the appearance of socio-hydrological models has encouraged hydrologists to reevaluate the way in which hydrological models are conceptualised, interrogated and evaluated \citep{}. Hydrological models are associated with a large amount of epistemic uncertainty arising from a lack of knowledge about the appropriate mathematical representation of hydrological processes at different spatial scales, a lack of knowledge about the physical properties and boundary conditions of catchments and a lack of knowledge about the reliability of input and validation datasets \citep{beven_changing_1989}. The various models accumulated by the hydrological modelling community may be viewed as working hypotheses about the hydrological behaviour of a place (refs). A large number of socio-hydrological models are stylized models which are used for developing hypotheses, advancing theories of co-evolutionary processes... At the same time, however, there is a need to develop models of real-world case studies, in order to identify gaps in our knowledge... This idea... Model-Data-Model paradigm elucidated by \citet{dibaldassare_???_2019} is essential in modelling efforts which seek to include human processes. The model is an attempt to apply the principles of socio-hydrology in a region where both hydrological and socioeconomic data is scarce, but where there is a clear need for improved understanding of the relationship between human and natural systems. As \citet{srinivasan_???_2018} point out, ``the basic premise of is that we stand to gain a lot more if we underpin our models on extant socio-economic and socio-ecological systems theories''. \\

At least partly this may originate from the strong focus on hydrological modelling as a predictive tool... with a focus on calibration and validation against observred hydrological outputs \citep{beven_modelling_2001}. However, the notion of hydrological models representing hypotheses of the system, and of modelling itself as a learning process, has gained traction in the community... \citep[e.g.][]{hrachowitz_decade_2013}. In this light, numerical modelling has emerged as an important mode of inquiry to advance our understanding of socio-hydrological systems \citep{}. \\

% Paragraph 4: discussion of super-individual concept
A key challenge of including human-water feedbacks within a spatially distributed framework is to efficiently represent human processes. Scale... The super-individual concept adopted here overcomes some of the issues associated with each approach. Clearly, it is not applicable in all... However, we argue that it provides a conceptual framework within which to consider different types of water user, and bridge the gap between top down approaches, which tend to consider society as a homogeneous entity, and agent-based approaches which considered individuals. Accounting for variability within each super-farm is possible through the use of probability distributions. In the absence of observed data... Knowledge of the statistical properties of water users is a key research gap. Since the ... adapts the approach... There are a number of improvements that could be made to the concept in order to make it more relevant to other sectors. At present, the super-individuals are treated independently, so that, for example, emergent behaviour in one super-individual does not influence the rate at which such behaviour may emerge in another. This may be relevant when considering the adoption of new technologies. It may also be relevant in considering the different levels of influence that different parts of society have in adapting to hazards (think of the levee effect).\\

The data requirements of an agent-based model deploying the super-individual concept are no less than than would be the case for a standard model. The strength of the concept relies to a large extent on having enough data about the individuals to parameterise a probability distribution that captures the variability of the relevant attributes within the group. \\

% Paragraph 5: limitations, knowledge gaps and data needs
% Developing models of these systems is challenging for various reasons [...] It requires effective collaboration between diverse research communities in order to include the state of the art in terms of the knowledge and understanding of system components \citep{blair_socio-hydrological_2016}, which is often difficult \citep{montanari_panta_2013}.
Necessarily, the model presented here is a simplification of the actual system. For example, we have not considered the effect of irrigation practices on soil quality; an issue which is increasingly important in many parts of the Indo-Gangetic Plain and which has a dramatic effect on viability of farmland. Although we have considered population growth and demographic change as boundary conditions to the system, in reality these processes are intertwined with agricultural wellbeing and farm profitability. Running the model in historical mode has to some extent allowed us to ignore these complexities and use observed data to constrain the model. However, ultimately our intention is to run the model in predictive mode, for which it will be necessary to include some of these processes as endogenous. A basic assumption of the farmer behaviour module is that humans (farmers) will act rationally on the available information in order to promote their wellbeing. This is consistent with several other socio-hydrological models \citep[e.g.][]{}. Selection of endogenous and exogenous processes. Food production in the Indo-Gangetic Plain is intrinsically linked to the national and global economy. According to \citet{pande_progress_2017}, ``in the context of socio-hydrology, a system is open if there are fluxes that flow across system boundaries''. ``Local water resources are used to produce commodities that are consumed in distant places (Konar et al. 2011)'' \citep{srinivasan_prediction_2016}. Currently, therefore, we treat farm size as an exogenous variable to the model. Clearly, farm size is intrinsically linked to the socioeconomic system. \\

The coupled model of the Gandak basin reveals several knowledge gaps. Many of these concern the physical system. The availability of river and canal discharge data in northern India is poor. Soil properties are derived from global datasets associated with a large amount of uncertainty \citep{}. Aside from uncertainty about the physical system, there are large gaps in understanding of smallholder systems. We have taken a water-centred approach, because fieldwork and reviews of the literature showed that this is an important variable. However, there are myriad other factors which influence farmer behaviour. Soil salinity is an important factor across the basin. To develop better models there is a need to identify the strengths and weaknesses of current models and highlight the processes and systems that are poorly understood in order to drive the collection of new or more accurate data and devise field studies of specific processes (refs). This is one of the main aims of uncertainty analysis (refs) and fundamental to the notion of modelling as a learning process. A lack of discourse between modellers and and field experimentalists means that that the current generation of hydrological models do not always reflect the advances in process understanding gained from field studies \citep{mcdonnell_moving_2007,clark_framework_2008}. The process of building the model has provided insight into the sort of data required to build spatially-explicit models which incorporate social processes, and highlighted gaps in current data. Some of these have started to be addressed in recent years. For example, there has been a new focus on land system maps. The IIASA-IFPRI cropland map was accompanied by a map of estimated field size, which is known to correlate with socioeconomic variables such as the degree of mechanization (refs). \\

